9 SECTION 4. G.S. 87-126 reads as rewritten:
10 "§ 87-126. Notification required when damage is done.done; venue.
11 (a) The excavator performing an excavation or demolition that results in any damage to
12 a facility shall immediately upon discovery of the damage notify the Notification Center and the
13 facility operator, if known, of the location and nature of the damage. The excavator shall allow
14 the operator reasonable time to accomplish necessary repairs before completing the excavation
15 or demolition in the immediate area of the facility. The excavator shall delay any backfilling in
16 the immediate area of the damaged facility until authorized by the operator. The operator or
17 qualified personnel authorized by the operator shall repair any damage to the facility.
18 (b) An excavator who is responsible for an excavation or demolition where any damage
19 to a facility results in the discharge of electricity or escape of any flammable, toxic, or corrosive
20 gas or liquid, or that endangers life, health, or property shall immediately notify emergency
21 responders, including 911 services, the Notification Center, and the facility operator. The
22 excavator shall take reasonable measures to protect himself or herself, other persons in immediate
23 danger, members of the general public, property, and the environment until the operator or
24 emergency responders arrive and complete an assessment of the situation.
25 (c) The venue for all actions arising out of physical damages to a facility or the failure of
26 a party to comply with the obligations imposed on that party by this Article shall be:
27 (1) As set forth in Article 7 of Chapter 1 of the General Statutes, where one or
28 more of the claims involve bodily injury or death.
29 (2) In the county where the facility that is the subject of the action is located, if
30 none of the claims involve bodily injury or death."
31 SECTION 5. G.S. 87-128 reads as rewritten:
32 "§ 87-128. Absence of facility location.
33 If an operator who has been given notice as provided in G.S. 87-120(d) by the Notification
34 Center fails to respond to that notice as provided in G.S. 87-121 or fails to properly locate the
35 facility, the person excavating is free to proceed with the excavation. Neither the excavator nor
36 the person financially responsible for the excavation will be liable to the nonresponding or
37 improperly responding operator for damages to the operator's facilities if the person doing the
38 excavating exercises due care to protect existing facilities when there is evidence of the existence
39 of those facilities near the proposed excavation area.so long as the excavator has exercised due
40 care in preparing for or conducting the excavation. For purposes of this section, the excavator
41 shall be entitled to a presumption, rebuttable by clear and convincing evidence, that it has
42 exercised due care in preparing for or conducting the excavation where all of the following apply:
43 (1) The Notification Center gives the operator the notice required in
44 G.S. 87-120(d).
45 (2) The operator fails to respond to that notice as provided in G.S. 87-121 or fails
46 to properly locate the facility.
47 (3) The excavator has complied with the requirements of G.S. 87-122(c).
48 (4) The excavator did not have actual knowledge of the existence of a facility
49 located within the area of the excavation to be performed."
50 SECTION 6. G.S. 87-129 reads as rewritten:
51 "§ 87-129. Underground Damage Prevention Review Board; enforcement; civil penalties.
Page 4 House Bill 247-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) There is hereby established the Underground Damage Prevention Review Board to
2 review reports of alleged violations of this Article. The members of the Board shall be appointed
3 by the Governor. The Board shall consist of 15 members as follows:
4 (1) A representative from the North Carolina Department of Transportation;
5 (2) A representative from a facility contract locator;
6 (3) A representative from the Notification Center;
7 (4) A representative from an electric public utility;
8 (5) A representative from the telecommunications industry;
9 (6) A representative from a natural gas utility;
10 (7) A representative from a hazardous liquid transmission pipeline company;
11 (8) A representative of a municipality, appointed on the recommendation of the
12 League of Municipalities;
13 (9) A highway contractor licensed under G.S. 87-10(b)(2) who does not own or
14 operate facilities;
15 (10) A public utilities contractor licensed under G.S. 87-10(b)(3) who does not
16 own or operate facilities;
17 (11) A surveyor licensed under Chapter 89C of the General Statutes;
18 (12) A representative from a rural water system, appointed on the recommendation
19 of the North Carolina Rural Water Association;
20 (13) A representative from an investor-owned water system;
21 (14) A representative from an electric membership corporation; and
22 (15) A representative from a cable company, appointed on the recommendation of
23 the North Carolina Cable Telecommunications Association.
24 (a1) Each member of the Board shall be appointed for a term of four years. Members of
25 the Board may serve no more than two consecutive terms. Vacancies in appointments made by
26 the Governor occurring prior to the expiration of a term shall be filled by appointment for the
27 unexpired term. To the extent practicable, the Governor shall fill any vacancy in appointment
28 within 60 days after the vacancy.
29 (a2) No member of the Board may serve on a case where there would be a conflict of
30 interest.
31 (a3) The Governor may remove any member at any time for cause.
32 (a4) Eight members A majority of the seated members of the Board shall constitute a
33 quorum. Board members may appear at meetings by simultaneous communication via conference
34 telephone or other electronic means.
35 (a5) The Governor shall designate one member of the Board as chair.
36 (a6) The Board may adopt rules to implement this Article.
37 (a7) The Board shall establish an internal attendance policy. In the event that a Board
38 member resigns or fails to meet the criteria of the attendance policy, the Board may appoint an
39 interim member to represent the same stakeholder group until such time as the Governor appoints
40 a replacement for the unexpired term.
41 (a8) On request of the Board, the Utilities Commission shall appoint a nonvoting ex officio
42 member as an administrative representative to provide counsel and coordinate efforts of the
43 Board.
44 (b) The Board shall receive reports of alleged violations of this Article. The Board shall
45 contact persons against whom reports have been filed to inform them of the alleged violation
46 within 10 days 15 working days of the filing of the report. The Board shall maintain all of the
47 following information regarding reports of alleged violations:
48 (1) The name, address, and telephone number of the person making the report;
49 (2) The nature of the report, including the statute that is alleged to have been
50 violated;
House Bill 247-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Information provided by the person making the report, including
2 correspondence, both written and electronic, pictures, and videos; and
3 (4) Information provided by the person against whom the report has been filed,
4 including correspondence, both written and electronic, pictures, and videos.
5 (b1) The Board shall review all reports of alleged violations of this Article and
6 accompanying information. If the Board determines that a person has violated any provision of
7 this Article, the Board shall determine the appropriate action or penalty to impose for each such
8 violation. Actions and penalties may include training, education, and a civil penalty not to exceed
9 two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500). The Board shall approve training courses and the
10 sponsors of those training courses under this subsection. Any fees for training courses approved
11 by the Board shall be paid by the person determined to have violated this Article. The Board shall
12 notify within 30 days each person who is determined to have violated this Article in writing of
13 the Board's determination and the Board's recommended action or penalty. A person determined
14 to be in violation of this Article may request a hearing before the Board, after which the Board
15 may reverse or uphold its original finding. If the Board recommends a penalty, the Board shall
16 notify the Utilities Commission of the recommended penalty, and the Utilities Commission shall
17 issue an order imposing the penalty.
18 (c) Notwithstanding Chapter 150B of the General Statutes, a person determined to be in
19 violation of this Article may request an informal conference before the Board by notifying the
20 Board in writing within 30 days of the Board's determination. The person must attend the
21 informal conference in person. The person may be represented by an attorney and may present
22 evidence and make arguments in favor of the person's position. Following the informal
23 conference, the Board may reverse, modify, or uphold its original finding. If the Board
24 recommends a penalty, the Board shall notify the Utilities Commission of the recommended
25 penalty, and the Utilities Commission shall issue an order imposing the penalty within 30 days
26 of notification by the Board.
27 (c1) A person determined by the Board under subsection (b1) of this section to have
28 violated this Article may appeal the Board's determination by initiating an arbitration proceeding
29 before the Utilities Commission within 30 days of the Board's determination. determination
30 following the informal conference. If the violating party elects to initiate an arbitration
31 proceeding, the violating party shall pay a filing fee of two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) to the
32 Utilities Commission, and the Utilities Commission shall open a docket regarding the report. The
33 Utilities Commission shall direct the parties enter into an arbitration process. The parties shall be
34 responsible for selecting and contracting with the arbitrator. Upon completion of the arbitration
35 process, the Utilities Commission shall issue an order encompassing the outcome of the binding
36 arbitration process, including a determination of fault, a penalty, and assessing the costs of
37 arbitration to the non-prevailing party.
38 (c1)(c2) A person may timely appeal an order issued by the Utilities Commission pursuant
39 to this section to the superior court division of the General Court of Justice in the county where
40 the alleged violation of this Article occurred or in Wake County, for trial de novo within 30 days
41 of entry of the Utilities Commission's order. The authority granted to the Utilities Commission
42 within this section is limited to this section and does not grant the Utilities Commission any
43 authority that they are not otherwise granted under Chapter 62 of the General Statutes.
44 (d) The provisions of this Article do not affect any civil remedies for personal injury or
45 property damage otherwise available to any person, except as otherwise specifically provided for
46 in this Article. The penalty provisions of this Article are cumulative to and not in conflict with
47 provisions of law with respect to civil remedies for personal injury or property damage. The clear
48 proceeds of any civil penalty assessed under this section shall be used as provided in Section 7(a)
49 of Article IX of the North Carolina Constitution. In any arbitration proceeding before the Utilities
50 Commission, any actions and penalties assessed against any person for violation of this Article
51 shall include the actions and penalties set out in subsection (b1) of this section.
Page 6 House Bill 247-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d1) The Utilities Commission shall report to the Board by March 1 of each year the
2 compliance of persons upon whom fines or penalties have been imposed under this Article.
3 (d2) If the amount of a penalty imposed by the Utilities Commission pursuant to subsection
4 (c) of this section is not paid to the Utilities Commission within 90 days of the Utilities
5 Commission issuing the order, the Attorney General, at the request of the Utilities Commission,
6 shall bring an action in the name of the State of North Carolina in the Wake County Superior
7 Court to recover the penalty. The action shall not commence until after the time has expired for
8 an appeal from the findings, conclusions, and order of the Utilities Commission.
9 (e) The Board is authorized to employ contractors or other personnel as it may deem
10 necessary to carry out the provisions of this Article.
11 (f) The Board shall maintain a record of reports of alleged violations of this Article
12 received under subsection (b) of this section for at least four years, including responses to such
13 reports.
14 (g) On request of the Board, the Attorney General's office shall assign a legal
15 representative to provide legal counsel to the Board."
16 SECTION 7. This act becomes effective September 1, 2025.
